Content: At a planetarium, Amy learns that Venus and Earth are sometimes called sister planets. To understand why, she begins to gather data on the planets. Some of the data on Venus are from observations that scientists made from Earth. Other data are from observations made by spacecraft sent to Venus beginning in the 1960s.
Amy decides to put the data into two tables, based on the source of the observations about Venus.
problems/NMG8S/media/1a.jpg
problems/NMG8S/media/1b.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which data are evidence that Earth and Venus are similar enough to be called sister planets?

A.Choice: diameter and density

B.Choice: mass and surface water

C.Choice: atmosphere and internal structure

D.Choice: surface gravity and daily surface temperature

Content: Which statement describes a reason that the differences between Earth and Venus have only been discovered since the 1960s?

A.Choice: The differences can only be observed from distances close to Venus.

B.Choice: The differences have developed since space-based observations began.

C.Choice: The differences result from changes in the way the spacecraft collect data.

D.Choice: The differences are caused by processes that recently began to occur on Venus.

Content: Elaine is researching the characteristics of sound waves as she listens to music. She finds a diagram that shows two sound waves.
problems/NMG8S/media/2a.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which statement describes the sound waves in the diagram?

A.Choice: Wave 1 has one-fourth the energy of Wave 2.s

B.Choice: Wave 1 has one-half the energy of Wave 2.

C.Choice: Wave 1 has twice the energy of Wave 2.

D.Choice: Wave 1 has four times the energy of Wave 2.

Content: Elaine predicts that the energy in each sound wave would double if the frequency of the wave doubled.
Which statement describes her prediction?

A.Choice: Her prediction is correct because the energy of a wave is proportional to the wave's frequency.

B.Choice: Her prediction is incorrect because the energy of a wave is proportional to the square of the wave's frequency.

C.Choice: Her prediction is correct because the energy of a wave is proportional to speed and a wave with twice the frequency has twice the speed.

D.Choice: Her prediction is incorrect because the energy of a wave is proportional to the wavelength and a wave with twice the frequency has half the wavelength.

Content: Sara learns about a fish called the tomcod. She learns that some tomcod have a genetic mutation that keeps PCB from entering the tomcod's cells. PCB is a poison that can kill fish.
The tomcod lives in rivers near the Atlantic Ocean like the Hudson River and the Squamscott River. The Hudson River is polluted with the chemical PCB.
The map shows two tomcod populations in the Hudson and Squamscott Rivers and the relative number of fish with the mutation in each population.
problems/NMG8S/media/3a.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Scientists are investigating how organisms become resistant to the harmful effects of PCB.
Based on the map, which statement describes the effects of the mutation on the Hudson River tomcod population?

A.Choice: Over time, the mutation has become more common in the population because having the mutation helps tomcod survive.

B.Choice: Over time, the mutation will move to the Squamscott tomcod population because that population also needs the mutation.

C.Choice: Over time, the mutation will pass from tomcod to other fish because tomcod with the mutation will mate with other species of fish.

D.Choice: Over time, the mutation has become less common in the population because the mutation does not produce more food for tomcod.

Content: Scientists are considering transporting some of the Hudson River tomcod to the Squamscott River.
Which statement describes a possible effect on the Squamscott River tomcod population?

A.Choice: Over time, more Squamscott tomcod will have the mutation if there are low levels of PCB in the Squamscott River.

B.Choice: Over time, more Squamscott tomcod will have the mutation if there are high levels of PCB in the Squamscott River.

C.Choice: Over time, fewer Squamscott tomcod will have the mutation if there are low levels of PCB in the Squamscott River.

D.Choice: Over time, fewer Squamscott tomcod will have the mutation if there are high levels of PCB in the Squamscott River.

Content: Rosanna's family is planning a vacation to a city on the ocean. Three places they are interested in visiting are Caracas, Venezuela; Myrtle Beach, South Carolina; and Casablanca, Morocco. The locations of these cities are shown on the map.
problems/NMG8S/media/4a.jpg
Rosanna begins researching the climate in each city. The table shows the average high and low temperatures for each city.
problems/NMG8S/media/4b.jpg

Rosanna wonders why three cities on the ocean have different average temperatures. She knows that energy from the Sun is a major factor that determines climate. She studies a model that shows energy from the Sun reaching Earth's surface. The model also shows the locations of the three cities.
problems/NMG8S/media/4c.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS THREE PARTS.
Use the model to explain ONE reason for the difference in temperature between Caracas and Myrtle Beach.
Rosanna thinks that adding ocean current information to the model would help explain the temperature differences between the three cities.

Describe ocean currents that could be added to the model to provide another reason for the differences in temperature between the cities. Be sure to include the direction and temperature of the currents near Caracas, Myrtle Beach, and Casablanca.
Use the model to describe how energy from the Sun causes the ocean currents described in the answer to Part (b).
Which statement is supported by the model?

A.Choice: Two carbon atoms and one oxygen molecule can form two carbon dioxide molecules.

B.Choice: One carbon dioxide molecule can form from one carbon atom and one oxygen molecule.

C.Choice: One carbon atom and one oxygen molecule have more mass than one carbon dioxide molecule.

D.Choice: Two carbon dioxide molecules have less mass than two carbon atoms and two oxygen molecules.

How does the model show that matter is conserved in chemical reactions?

A.Choice: The properties of substances change over time.

B.Choice: A substance is made of different kinds of atoms.

C.Choice: The atoms in substances are too small to be seen.

Content: THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which statement describes how humpback whales depend on photosynthesis to survive?

A.Choice: Humpback whales use photosynthesis to provide energy to perform cellular functions.

B.Choice: Phytoplankton use photosynthesis to produce sugars that are passed on to the prey of humpback whales.

C.Choice: Photosynthesis in humpback whales uses solar energy to produce matter that phytoplankton need to grow.

D.Choice: Humpback whales use photosynthesis to produce sugars that other organisms in the food web use for energy.

Content: Which evidence from the food web diagram supports the answer to Part (a)?

A.Choice: Humpback whales prey on large fish and sea lions.

B.Choice: Humpback whales and sea lions are prey for orcas.

C.Choice: Humpback whales eat large fish that eat zooplankton.

D.Choice: Humpback whales eat small fish that eat phytoplankton.

Content: Based on the diagram, which TWO statements explain how warm-water phytoplankton disrupt the food web?

A.Choice: Warm-water phytoplankton add matter and energy that are available in the system for cold-water phytoplankton.

B.Choice: Warm-water phytoplankton outcompete cold-water phytoplankton for carbon dioxide and nutrients needed for growth.

C.Choice: Large fish and sea lions receive more matter and energy from warm-water phytoplankton than from cold-water phytoplankton.

D.Choice: Zooplankton and small fish receive less matter and energy from warm-water phytoplankton than from cold-water phytoplankton.

E.Choice: Harmful warm-water phytoplankton consume cold-water phytoplankton instead of using photosynthesis to produce matter and energy for the ecosystem.

Content: Elias wants to make a model that shows some of the interactions between humpback whales and their environment. An incomplete model is shown in the diagram.
problems/NMG8S/media/11a.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which labels BEST complete the model?

A.Choice:
1 = increase in prey

2 = decrease in prey

3 = increase in warm-water phytoplankton

B.Choice:
1 = decrease in prey

2 = increase in warm-water phytoplankton 3 = decrease in warm-water phytoplankton

C.Choice:
1 = increase in warm-water phytoplankton

2 = decrease in warm-water phytoplankton

3 = increase in prey

D.Choice:
1 = decrease in warm-water phytoplankton

2 = increase in prey

3 = decrease in prey

Content: Which relationship between environmental factors and humpback whale birth rates is supported by the model in Part (a)?

A.Choice: A decrease in warm-water phytoplankton caused whale reproduction to stop completely.

B.Choice: An increase in warm-water phytoplankton caused more male whale deaths than female whale deaths.

C.Choice: An increase in prey caused faster growth, so younger whales were able to leave the area to find more food.

D.Choice: A decrease in prey caused more competition, so whales had less energy to find mates and produce healthy offspring.

Content: Elias wonders what would happen if warm water became the normal condition in this cold-water ocean ecosystem.
Which prediction is supported by the food web diagram and graph?

A.Choice: The whale population would increase because warm water increases the amount of food available for cold-water species.

B.Choice: The whale population would decrease because warm water decreases the amount of nutrient-rich food available for cold-water species.

C.Choice: The whale population would increase because prey species are better able to survive and reproduce when water temperatures are warmer.

D.Choice: The whale population would decrease because prey species are better able to survive and reproduce when water temperatures are normal.

Content: While Vanessa helps her grandmother feed the chickens, she notices a chicken embryo inside a broken egg. Vanessa observes that the chicken embryo has a long tail. She asks her grandmother why the embryo has a long tail, but an adult chicken does not. Her grandmother encourages her to learn more about how chickens develop.
Vanessa finds a table that shows how the embryos of several types of animals change before birth. The table also shows an adult of each type of animal.
problems/NMG8S/media/13a.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Vanessa observes similarities and differences in the organisms' patterns of growth at different stages of development.
Which TWO patterns are supported by the information in the table?

A.Choice: The organisms look most similar just before birth.

B.Choice: All the organisms have large heads in stage 2 and stage 3.

C.Choice: The organisms become smaller between stage 3 and stage 4.

D.Choice: All the organisms have relatively long tails in stage 2 and stage 3.

E.Choice: Differences among the organisms increase from stage 1 to stage 5.

Content: Which relationship among the organisms is supported by the patterns in Part (a)?

A.Choice: The organisms have a common ancestor.

B.Choice: The embryos of larger animals develop slowly.

C.Choice: The organisms appeared on Earth at about the same time.

D.Choice: The embryos spend different amounts of time at each stage of development.

Content: While reading a book about rain forests, Becca learns that many of the zoo animals are from tropical areas on Earth, but that the animals' natural habitats are disappearing. After some research, Becca finds that these tropical areas used to have very large rain forests, but that the rain forests are disappearing as humans begin to use the land. The table and graph show types of human activities and their effects on the deforestation of tropical areas.
problems/NMG8S/media/14a.jpg
problems/NMG8S/media/14b.jpg
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Based on the table and the graph, which change could cause the MOST positive impact on the forests in tropical areas?

A.Choice: eating less meat from cattle

B.Choice: growing crops that need less fertilizer

C.Choice: encouraging more families to own farms

D.Choice: building homes from materials other than wood

Content: The human population is increasing quickly in tropical areas. Which solution could help reduce deforestation in these areas without hurting people?

A.Choice: Bring small farms together to form larger farms in the forest.

B.Choice: Teach people how to safely cook and store meat from cattle.

C.Choice: Require that houses be built on land where forests are cut down.

D.Choice: Find ways to use less farmland to grow the same amount of food.

Content: In class, Henry learns that all bees gather food and nesting materials from plants. He learns that orchid bees and orchid plants have a special relationship. Henry made a list of information about the relationship.

:ibox: The orchids that orchid bees visit do not make nesting materials or food that bees can eat.

 Male orchid bees choose to visit orchid plants that have flowers that produce fragrant oils with strong scents.

 Male orchid bees collect these fragrant oils and store them on their bodies.

 Female orchid bees are attracted to the scent of the fragrant oils on male orchid bees.

 Male and female orchid bees do not live together in a large hive. Female orchid bees mate with male orchid bees only once in their lifetime.

 Orchid plants are pollinated when male orchid bees carry pollen from flower to flower.
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Construct an argument that the behavior of individual orchid bees affects reproduction in the orchid bee population. Be sure to use information that Henry learned to support your argument.
One scientist argues that orchid plants have evolved to produce the specific scents that attract female orchid bees.
Support the scientist's claim with evidence that explains how the oil produced by an orchid plant affects the reproduction of the orchid species.
The winter months in Perth are June, July, and August. Like other locations with a Mediterranean climate, Perth has mild, rainy winters.

A.Choice: rising air temperatures

B.Choice: rising ocean temperatures

C.Choice: winds blowing from the northwest

D.Choice: decreasing levels of humidity in the air

Content: In some areas with a Mediterranean climate, mountains rise just beyond the coastline. During the rainy winter, rainfall varies greatly with distance from the ocean. Locations that are high on the slopes of mountains and face the ocean receive the most rainfall.
Which statement describes why these locations receive the most rain?

A.Choice: Air at these locations causes changes in weather and precipitation.

B.Choice: Air that has risen to these locations is cooler and releases more precipitation.

C.Choice: Air that has risen to these locations has faster winds during rainstorms.

D.Choice: Air at these locations receives enough sunlight to become warm enough for rain to fall.

Content: Kevin claims that all locations with a Mediterranean climate do not have exactly the same climate. He claims that the geography of the land can influence climate.
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which evidence could support Kevin's claim?

A.Choice: Two cities at different latitudes are the same distance from the ocean and have the same climate.

B.Choice: Two cities at the same latitude are different distances from the ocean and have the same climate.

C.Choice: Two cities at different latitudes are at the same elevation above sea level and have different climates.

D.Choice: Two cities at the same latitude are at different elevations above sea level and have different climates.

Content: Which other factor could cause the climates in these locations to be SLIGHTLY different?

A.Choice: the average monthly wind speed at each location

B.Choice: the average daily high and low temperatures at each location

C.Choice: the amount of vegetation that covers the land at each location

D.Choice: the amount of precipitation during each season at each location

Content: Kevin studies the graph of weather data for Los Angeles and all that he learned during his research.

Content: Which additional data could support the claim that air movements change weather conditions in Los Angeles?

Content: THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.

Content: Eric wants to understand how wearing seat belts in a car can keep people safe during collisions.
To investigate how a seat belt works, he puts a wooden block inside a toy car as shown in the diagram.
problems/NMG8S/media/24a.jpg
He pushes the car into a wall and observes that the block falls out of the car. Then he attaches a belt around the block as shown in the diagram.

Content: Jessica's dog just had puppies. The parent dogs both have black fur, but some of the puppies have brown fur. Jessica wonders how that can happen. She learns that the gene that controls brown or black fur color in dogs has two alleles: dominant B and recessive b. If a dog has one or two dominant B alleles, the dog has black fur. If a dog has two recessive b alleles, the dog has brown fur.
Jessica wants to make a model to show how parents with black fur can have puppies with brown fur.
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which model could Jessica make to BEST represent how parents with black fur can have puppies with brown fur?

A.Choice: problems/NMG8S/media/25a.jpg

B.Choice: problems/NMG8S/media/25b.jpg

C.Choice: problems/NMG8S/media/25c.jpg

D.Choice: problems/NMG8S/media/25d.jpg

Content: If the two parent dogs described in Part (a) have a litter of four puppies, what is the MOST LIKELY number of puppies with brown fur?

A.Choice: two, because both parents have one B allele and one b allele

B.Choice: two, because there is a 50% chance of a puppy with Bb alleles

C.Choice: one, because there is a 25% chance of a puppy with bb alleles

D.Choice: one, because there is a 25% chance of a puppy with BB alleles

Content: Bruce tells his grandparents that a new cell phone has much better sound quality than an old telephone. A phone with better sound quality produces sounds that are close to the original sounds. Sound quality is poor when sounds are distorted and are different from the original sounds.

To learn more, Bruce finds that both cell phones and old telephones convert sound information into signals that are transmitted from one phone to another. He finds that telephones use analog signals and cell phones use digital signals. Information about analog and digital signals is shown in the table.
problems/NMG8S/media/26a.jpg

The table shows that the amplitude of analog signals varies smoothly, while the amplitude of digital signals does not. The table also shows the signals when they reach the listener's phone and after they have been converted to sound in the listener's phone.
THIS PROBLEM HAS TWO PARTS.
Which claim is supported by data in the table?

A.Choice: Noise does not affect digital signals.

B.Choice: Information cannot be carried by analog signals.

C.Choice: Analog signals are more distorted than digital signals.

D.Choice: Digital signals are easier to transmit than analog signals.

Content: Which statement is supported by the information Bruce found?

A.Choice: Digital signals are easier to store than analog signals.

B.Choice: Digital signals can be transmitted over longer distances than analog signals.

C.Choice: Digital signals can be converted back to sound with all of the original characteristics.

D.Choice: Digital signals contain more information about the original sound than analog signals.

Content: It is a very cold day in the middle of January and twin sisters Sara and Kara are excited to celebrate their birthday. They decide to buy helium-filled balloons for their birthday party. When they arrive at the store, they choose several large balloons.

As the girls walk home through the snow, they notice that the balloons shrink and become smaller even though there are no leaks in the balloons. However, after the girls take the balloons inside their home, the balloons return to their original size.

The girls wonder whether the change in the balloons was caused by the change in temperature. They find out that the temperature of the cold air outside their home is -2C and the temperature of the warm air inside their home and the store is 21C. They decide to use a model to show how temperature affects the size of a helium- filled balloon.
THIS PROBLEM HAS THREE PARTS.
Draw models to compare a helium-filled balloon in three locations: inside the store, outside during the walk home, and inside the home. In each model, be sure to include:

:ibox: the arrangement and spacing of the helium particles inside the balloon.

 the temperature of the helium-filled balloon.
Describe how the motion of the helium particles inside each balloon changes when the girls take the balloons out of the store to walk home. Be sure to include the reason for the change in motion.
Use your models and the motion of the helium particles to explain why the balloons become smaller during the walk home.
Xavier wants to make a model that shows how matter moves in the forest ecosystem.
